text: So basically most geniuses are assbags, like that guy who built the Enigma machine decoder. Safe to say because we're all idiots and troglodytes in their eyes spending our money on things we dont need. Making the rich richer while us consumers get poorer. Genius. I guess I can imagine his frustration since I've watched enough of Sheldon Cooper through the years. I get it, ethics and social grace seem to become more of an inconvenience when your mind is processing faster than the average man-monkey. They probably dont mean to be cold or selfish or condescending, but it takes too much precious time to explain and apologize for something they have preconceived we'd never accept or understand. So they carry on, because greater things are at play that exceed our petty sensitivities. I honestly hate what the iphone has done to people. Nobody ever hardly looks up anymore. People walking past each other on the streets oblivious to whats in front of them. Entire families sitting at a restaurant quietly tapping away their time together. The very thing that's supposed to bring people together is the very same thing that keeps them apart...  Genius...If you're the devil...

text: This movie was sensational.  The only flaw, in my opinion, was Seth Rogan who simply cannot act.  But the rest of the cast is outstanding.  Jeff Daniels and Michael Stuhlberg were great in their supporting roles, and Kate Winslet really should have won her second oscar for her work.  She carries the audience with her on her shoulders throughout the very complicated structure of the film, and manages to be the one person who legitimately convinces Steve of anything at all, and she does it all while giving Joanna Hoffman believably strong and unique personality touches while also seeming fiercely professional and loyal.  It's a really great performance from her and also Michael Fassbender was wonderful in the lead role as well.  I think he too should have won the oscar that year.
